{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778291251,"nonce":"2hAZgf6r7X3un34vNHXNhLmdvlk=","title":"Investigate: low-rank recurrent constraint as alternative to GRU/vRNN for variance reduction","message":"## What is it\n\nThe low-rank RNN constraint sets the recurrent weight matrix W_rec = U V^T where U, V ∈ R^{N×R} with R \u003c\u003c N (rank R). This reduces the dimensionality of the trajectory manifold to R and makes the network's fixed-point structure analytically tractable (Mastrogiuseppe \u0026 Ostojic 2018, Neuron). The network is parameterised directly in terms of U and V instead of a full N×N matrix.\n\n## Seminal literature\n\n- **Mastrogiuseppe \u0026 Ostojic 2018** (Neuron): foundational. Derives mean-field theory for low-rank connectivity. Connectivity = random + low-rank structured term. Analyzes Go/No-Go tasks, discrimination tasks. NOT motor reaching tasks specifically.\n- **Beiran et al. 2021** (Neural Computation): extends to mixture-of-Gaussians populations; shows rank R suffices for R-dimensional dynamics when population structure is present. Tasks: decision-making, working memory.\n- **Dubreuil et al. 2022** (Nat Neurosci): trains low-rank RNNs on 5 neuroscience tasks — perceptual decision-making, parametric working memory, multi-sensory DM, contextual DM, delay-match-to-sample. Finds flexible input-output mappings require non-random population structure, not just increased rank. No motor reaching tasks.\n\n## Use in motor control\n\nThe framework has NOT been applied to delayed-reach motor control tasks like center-out reaching in the published literature surveyed. Michaels et al. 2020 PNAS uses full-rank RNN with ReTanh nonlinearity and no low-rank constraint. Shahbazi et al. 2025 uses full-rank GRUs. The low-rank literature is predominantly decision-making and working-memory.\n\n## Relevance to our setting\n\nIn our setup (180-unit GRU, adversarial training), the recurrent weight matrix is already full-rank and unconstrained. A low-rank constraint would:\n(a) directly limit the dimensionality of hidden-state trajectories across replicates, potentially reducing variability\n(b) make the network's solutions analytically tractable post-hoc\n(c) require re-implementing the GRU recurrent block as a parameterised U@V.T product — non-trivial in feedbax\n\nAn intermediate approach is already tracked at cf56e1e (rank-1 to full-GRU capacity ablation). That issue tests rank empirically using trained networks, not by constraining training.\n\n## Implementation cost\n\nConstrained low-rank training requires either: (a) replacing the GRU hidden-hidden weight with U@V.T (breaks standard GRU equations), or (b) using a plain RNNCell with a structured weight. Feedbax does not currently support this. Non-trivial to add without feedbax changes.\n\n## When relevant\n\nOnly if full-rank GRU, smoothness penalty (efc4d68), activity L2 bump (83ba749), and vRNN ablation all fail to reduce replicate variability to usable levels.\n\n## Cross-refs\n\nTraining-methods coord c99ad9d. Smoothness umbrella efc4d68 (escalation step #4). Capacity-restricted RNN ablation cf56e1e (related: tests rank effect empirically). Activity L2 bump 83ba749 (prior escalation step).","files":null}]}